@startuml fig-ftp-active-vs-passive
skinparam backgroundColor white
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center

title FTP active mode vs passive mode

participant "FTP Client" as C #FFE0B2
participant "FTP Server\n(port 21)" as S #C8E6C9

== Active mode ==

C -> S : PORT <client-ip>,<client-port>
note right of C
  Client opens a listener.
  Server initiates the
  data connection back.
end note
S -> C : <color:#1565C0>data connection (server → client)</color>
S --> C : file content
C -> S : ACK (transfer complete)

== Passive mode ==

C -> S : PASV
S --> C : 227 Entering Passive Mode (<server-port>)
note right of S
  Server opens a listener.
  Client initiates the
  data connection forward.
end note
C -> S : <color:#43A047>data connection (client → server)</color>
S --> C : file content
C -> S : ACK (transfer complete)

legend bottom
  Active mode fails behind NAT/firewalls (server cannot reach client).
  Passive mode works because the client initiates both connections.
  Passive mode is the default in virtually all modern FTP clients.
endlegend
@enduml
